          <h2 class="tldr__heading">Verdict</h2>
          <div class="verdict">
            <div class="verdict__side">
              <h3>Kintone wins for</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Internal workflow tools (project mgmt, approvals, inventory, custom apps)</li>
                <li>Japan-domestic businesses with Japanese-first teams</li>
                <li>SMEs under 50 people without dedicated sales ops</li>
                <li>Flexibility and low-code configuration</li>
                <li>Cost-sensitive deployments</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict__side">
              <h3>Salesforce wins for</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Complex, high-volume B2B sales pipelines</li>
                <li>Businesses with 10+ dedicated sales staff</li>
                <li>Revenue forecasting, territory management, complex deal structures</li>
                <li>Parent-company ecosystem integration</li>
                <li>Mature AppExchange integration needs</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="verdict__conclusion">
            For most Japan SMEs under 50 people, <strong>Kintone is the right answer</strong>.
            Salesforce is a genuinely better product for the problems it's designed to solve, but
            but those problems aren't the ones most Japan SMEs actually have.
          </p>
        </aside>

